This page, for those who haven't already glazed over, endeavors to elucidate the arcane mechanics of creating various types of digital connections. Specifically, we're dissecting: (a) [links](/Hyperlink) that keep you tethered to other pages within the sacred confines of Wikipedia (affectionately known as **wikilinks**), those that daringly venture out to other Wikimedia projects (the **interwiki links**), and the ones that cast you adrift into the vast, unfiltered ocean of other websites (the **external links**). Furthermore, we'll touch upon (b) **anchors** – those specific points within pages that allow for precision targeting, like a digital sniper. For the overarching philosophical guidelines on how to actually *employ* these digital tethers with some semblance of grace, you'll need to consult the [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Linking](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Linking). Don't say I didn't warn you.

### Wikilinks (internal links)

*   See also: [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Linking](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Linking) and [Help:Wikitext § Wikilinks](/Help:Wikitext). Because one explanation is never enough, apparently.
*   For the syntax required to embed pictures and other assorted media files, you'll want to consult [Wikipedia:Extended image syntax](/Wikipedia:Extended_image_syntax). This page is about *links*, not your vacation photos.

A "wikilink," or as some prefer, an "internal link" – because clarity is always appreciated, even if rarely achieved – serves as the digital connective tissue between pages. It's designed to keep you firmly within the confines of the same Wikipedia project, whether you're navigating the hallowed halls of the English Wikipedia or, perhaps, diving into the linguistic abyss of [Wiktionary](/Wiktionary). Think of it as a meticulously crafted rabbit hole, but one that only ever leads to another part of the same warren. The idea, apparently, is to prevent you from wandering off to less... *curated* corners of the internet.

#### Basic syntax

The fundamental act of creating a wikilink is surprisingly simple, almost deceptively so. It's enclosed in doubled square brackets, like a fragile thought within a protective cage.

On any Wikimedia page, simply typing `[[1234]]` produces a wikilink. This digital artifact will display as the text [1234](/1234) and, upon interaction, will direct the user to the target page also named [1234](/1234) on the project you are currently inhabiting. To illustrate this point with unnecessary specificity, if you were to perform this on the English Wikipedia, the resulting wikilink would lead to the following URL (observe the tell-tale "en" nestled within the address, a subtle clue to your digital location): `https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1234`. It's a direct, unambiguous path, assuming the page `1234` actually exists. If not, well, we'll get to that existential dread later.

#### Section linking

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) (Another shortcut, for those who find the primary ones too... long.)
*   [H:WIKILINK](/H:WIKILINK) (Just in case you forgot what we're talking about.)
*   See also: [Help:Section § Section linking](/Help:Section), and [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Linking § Section links](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Linking). Because why explain it once when you can reference it thrice?

To link to a specific section or even a subsection nestled within another page, you must append a `#` symbol, followed by the precise name of the section, directly to the page name. It's like giving GPS coordinates within a document.

`[[Page name#Section name|Displayed text]]`

For those daring to link *within* the very page you're currently editing – a feat of self-referential digital acrobatics – you can simply omit the page name. Just use a `#` followed by the section name:

`[[#Section name|Displayed text]]`

Omitting the page name for same-page links is not merely a stylistic choice; it's a recommended practice. Why? Because it ensures the link continues to function as intended when you're previewing your changes, or, more crucially, after the page itself has been moved to a new digital address. It saves you from future headaches, a rare commodity in this realm.

Should you desire to format a link with the venerable [section sign](/Section_sign) (§) instead of the more utilitarian `#` (e.g., [Page name § Section name](/Special:PermanentLink/WP:Naming_conventions) rather than the blunt [Page name#Section name](/Page_name)), you can employ the {{[Section link](/Template:Section_link)}} template (which, in a moment of rare efficiency, also has the alias {{[slink](/Template:Slink)}}):

`{{Section link| Page name | Section name }}`

A critical detail, often overlooked by those who believe the digital world bends to their will: section names are **entirely case sensitive**. This stands in stark contrast to article links, where the initial character's capitalization is a mere suggestion. Ignore this at your peril; the system will not forgive your sloppiness.

Furthermore, the characters `[ ] { } |` (that's the right and left square [bracket](/Bracket), the right and left curly [braces](/Bracket), and the ubiquitous [vertical bar](/Vertical_bar)) demand special encoding when you're attempting to link directly to a section containing them. In layman's terms, you cannot simply shove these characters into the `[[ ]]` of a link and expect it to work. The system, in its infinite wisdom, will simply refuse. See note. [1]

For a deeper dive into the glorious intricacies of sections, consult [Help:Section](/Help:Section). And for the truly dedicated, or perhaps masochistic, consider [Wikipedia:Redirect § Targeted and untargeted redirects](/Wikipedia:Redirect). The rabbit hole, as always, goes deeper.

#### Alternate display text

*   See also: [Help:Piped link](/Help:Piped_link) and [Help:Pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick). Because sometimes, the name of the destination isn't what you want to show the tourists.

To craft a link that presents different text to the reader than the actual name of its target page, you must employ the [vertical bar](/Vertical_bar) `|` (colloquially known as the "[pipe](/Vertical_bar)" symbol). Such a link, a marvel of digital misdirection, is aptly termed a [piped link](/Help:Piped_link). Within the double square brackets `[[target|text]]`, the segment preceding the pipe dictates the true title of the link's destination page. The segment following the pipe, however, provides the cunningly chosen display text that the user will actually perceive:

*   `[[a|b]]` appears on the page as [b](/A), but, upon activation, it will dutifully transport the user to the page designated as [a](/A). The underlying URL, for the record, would be `https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A`. It's a simple sleight of hand, effective for those who don't scrutinize the destination too closely.

#### Display text agglutination

Letters and other non-punctuation characters that immediately follow the closing bracket of a wikilink – with absolutely no whitespace permitted in between – are automatically appended to the link's display text. The target of the link, thankfully, remains utterly oblivious to this textual accretion. This syntax, a small mercy in a world of complex rules, offers a concise shorthand: it allows you to link to an article by its canonical title while simultaneously displaying an inflected version of that title, ensuring grammatical harmony with the surrounding inline text. It's almost elegant, in a brutalist sort of way.

*   "There are over 7,500 known cultivars of [apples](/Apple)." Here, `[[apple]]s` gives the display text "apples" but directs the user to the target page [apple](/Apple). This shorthand is functionally identical to the more verbose `[[apple|apples]]`, saving you precious keystrokes and the existential dread of typing an extra pipe.

Illustrative examples of display text agglutination:

*   `[[a|b]]c` renders as [bc](/A), which is, for all intents and purposes, equivalent to having meticulously typed `[[a|bc]]`.
*   `a[[b]]` yields `a[b](/B)`. Observe, if you can bear to, that there are no special, convoluted rules governing text that *precedes* a wikilink. The system, for once, keeps it simple.
*   Should you wish to prepend text to a displayed link, the technique is straightforward: `[[b|ab]]` results in [ab](/B).
*   `[[a]]:b` produces [a](/A):b. A vital distinction here: punctuation characters, in their infinite wisdom, **break** the spell of display text agglutination. This particular quirk is often quite helpful, especially when dealing with possessives. For instance, `[[Batman]]'s` will correctly render as [Batman](/Batman)'s, rather than attempting to link the apostrophe and 's' into the Caped Crusader's very being.
*   `[[a]]''b''` gives [a](/A) b . Now, pay attention. Markup notation – such as the two sequential single quote characters used to delimit italics – is also considered punctuation. This means that any italic text immediately following a wikilink will **not** be absorbed into the displayed link. It stands apart, defiantly.
*   To successfully append italicized text to a displayed link, you must explicitly include it within the piped link itself: `[[a|a''b'']]` yields a b . A small detail, but one that separates the diligent from the perpetually frustrated.
*   `[[a]]<nowiki />b` results in [a](/A)b. The `<nowiki />` tag, a potent incantation, effectively disables the agglutination rule, allowing for precise control over your textual unions.
*   Similarly, `[[a|b]]<nowiki />c` produces [b](/A)c.

#### Advanced piping

For those who crave even greater efficiency in their digital labors, or simply wish to avoid the tiresome act of typing, consult [Help:Pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick). It offers further enlightenment on generating various forms of [piped links](/Help:Piped_link) without the need to manually input text after the [pipe](/Vertical_bar). Because who has time for that?

#### Target page

When a wikilink is invoked, Wikipedia's underlying machinery springs into action, diligently attempting to resolve the wikilink's target title to its definitive, **canonical** target page. The intricacies of this conversion process are further detailed in the section aptly titled "§ Conversion to canonical form," for those who enjoy plumbing the depths of digital esoterica.

Crucially, when this resolution process is underway, the target title is treated as case-sensitive, with one significant exception: the very first character. This minor concession to human fallibility means:

*   `[[atom]]` will dutifully link to [Atom](/Atom). The system, in this instance, understands your casual capitalization. The URL will be `https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom`.
*   However, `[[aTom]]` would, in its rigid adherence to the rules, attempt to link to a page literally titled "ATom." Such a page, in most sane wikis, [does not exist](/Wikipedia:Red_link), resulting in a rather conspicuous `https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ATom` leading to an empty void. Remember, the system is forgiving, but not *that* forgiving.

#### Disambiguation

When an edit is previewed, a crucial moment of reckoning occurs. If the intended target of your freshly minted link happens to be a [disambiguation page](/Wikipedia:DAB) – a digital crossroads, such as the [Peacemaker](/Peacemaker) page, offering multiple paths – then, unless your link is deliberately nestled within a [hatnote](/Wikipedia:HN) (a rare and specific use case), the link **must** be altered. It needs to be redirected to one of the specific choices presented on that disambiguation page. If necessary, and it often is, the new, more precise link can be [piped](/Wikipedia:Pipe). An example of such surgical precision would be `[[Peacemaker (character)|Peacemaker]]`, which, when rendered, appears as [Peacemaker](/Peacemaker_(character)) and, more importantly, correctly links to the article dedicated to the fictional character, rather than leaving the reader to ponder the various meanings of "Peacemaker."

A fundamental principle, often stated but rarely truly absorbed: readers should **never** be intentionally directed to a disambiguation page. It's a digital dead end, a signpost without a clear destination, unless, of course, there is absolutely no other viable option but to do so. And trust me, there's almost *always* another option.

#### Nonexistent page (red link)

*   See also: [Wikipedia:Red link](/Wikipedia:Red_link) and [Help:What links here](/Help:What_links_here). Because sometimes, the void stares back.

Should the target page of a wikilink be utterly nonexistent – a digital phantom – it will be conspicuously displayed in a vibrant red font. This scarlet beacon of absence is, quite fittingly, termed a "[red link](/Wikipedia:Red_link)":

This link is an example of a red link. A testament to ambition, or perhaps, oversight.

Upon hovering your cursor, with a morbid curiosity, over such a red link, a tooltip will emerge, offering meager information about the spectral destination. It's a small comfort, knowing *why* it's red.

If, against all good judgment, a red link is clicked, the user is transported to a blank expanse – a digital tabula rasa. On this empty canvas, the opportunity arises to *create* a page using that very red-linked title. While contemplating this act of digital creation, one can also employ the "[What links here](/Help:What_links_here)" feature to discover if other red links, perhaps from equally ambitious or forgetful editors, also point to this particular non-existent title. It's like finding fellow travelers to the edge of the known universe.

#### Self link

A [self link](/Help:Self_link) is, as the name subtly implies, a wikilink whose target page is identical to the very page on which it makes its appearance. In a fascinating act of digital self-reflection, self links do not behave like their more adventurous brethren. Instead of initiating an action upon interaction, they simply mimic regular body text, but with an added flourish: they are rendered as **bolded** body text. For example, `[[Help:Link]]` is a self link to *this very page*. Consequently, when viewed on this page, it appears as **Help:Link** and, upon interaction, remains stoically inert. It's a digital mirror, reflecting its own existence without further consequence.

#### Special wikilinks

Certain types of wikilink target pages trigger unique and often unexpected behaviors within the system. These are the exceptions that prove the rule, or perhaps just prove the complexity of the system:

*   `[[File:Mediawiki.png]]` does not simply link; it commands the linked [image](/Wikipedia:Images) to be rendered directly on the current page. It's an embed, not just a reference.
*   `[[Category:Help]]` doesn't just point to a category; it actively adds the current page to the specified [category](/Wikipedia:Categorization). A subtle but powerful act of classification.
*   `[[fr:Aide:Liens]]` conjures a meta [interlanguage link](/Help:Interlanguage_links), a bridge to the exact same article, but within a completely different linguistic iteration of Wikipedia. A digital Rosetta Stone, if you will.

However, should you wish to suppress these special behaviors and instead display a mundane, regular wikilink to these particular page types, you can achieve this by prepending a colon character `:` to the target page. It's a small act of rebellion against the system's default:

*   `[[:File:Mediawiki.png]]` gracefully yields a literal link, with its target page clearly identified as [File:Mediawiki.png](/File:Mediawiki.png). No image embedding, just a humble link.
*   `[[:Category:Help]]` likewise produces a literal link, directing you to the target page [Category:Help](/Category:Help), without the automatic categorization.
*   `[[:fr:Aide:Liens]]` transforms into the literal wikilink fr:Aide:Liens, pointing directly to the French Wikipedia page for Help:Link, without the interlanguage sidebar magic.

#### Uncommon link target interpretations

For those with an insatiable appetite for the obscure and the esoteric, less common ways in which link targets are reinterpreted by the system are meticulously detailed further below, under the ominous heading of "#Conversion to canonical form." Proceed with caution, for these are the true depths of digital esoterica.

#### Editing tools

When engaged in the sacred act of editing source code, the insertion or deletion of links is, in principle, a straightforward affair: simply add or remove pairs of square brackets enclosing the relevant text. Of course, this assumes you also gracefully handle the intricacies of piped links, because nothing is ever *truly* simple.

Fortunately, for those who prefer a gentler hand, or perhaps lack the raw willpower to type brackets manually, some helpful tools exist:

*   When you are utilizing the [visual editor](/Wikipedia:VisualEditor) – a graphical interface for the faint of heart – you can select a block of text, then click the rather intuitive link icon located above the text box (it resembles two links of a chain, a visual metaphor that even *you* might grasp). This action will summon a dialogue, allowing you to add the link, presenting a selection of possible matches, and even offering the ability to pipe the link. It's almost too easy.
*   For the more traditional, or perhaps stubborn, among us, the [WikEd](/Wikipedia:WikEd) source editor offers another path. This can be activated via `Preferences > Gadgets > Editing`. Within this venerable editor, a "Wiki link" button awaits your command (it's typically the very first button on the bottom row, hard to miss). When you're in the throes of editing, if you [highlight](/Selection_(user_interface)) some text, clicking this button will magically enclose it in double brackets, effectively "Wikilinking" it. Conversely, if you highlight text that *already* contains one or more internal links – often just a single link with its delimiting brackets – clicking the button will perform the inverse: it will remove them. For a solitary link without a pipe, the Wiki link button acts as a toggle, switching between linked and unlinked states. It's a small convenience, for those who appreciate such things.

### Interwiki links

*   See also: [Help:Interwiki linking](/Help:Interwiki_linking) and [Help:Interlanguage links](/Help:Interlanguage_links). Because the digital universe is vast, and sometimes you need to travel.

An [interwiki link](/Help:Interwiki_linking) is your digital passport, allowing you to connect to a page residing on an entirely different Wikimedia project website. This could be something as familiar as [Meta](/Meta-Wiki), or perhaps a distant cousin like another language Wikipedia. The crucial prerequisite is that the target site must be meticulously listed on the interwiki map designated for the source wiki. These links, in a display of structural consistency, employ the same `[[...]]` syntax as their wikilink counterparts (as previously discussed, if you were paying attention). However, they demand a specific prefix, `":x:"`, which precisely identifies the target site. It's like a special dialing code for the digital cosmos.

For instance, `[[m:Help:Link]]` will dutifully connect you to the "Help:Link" page on Meta, while `[[:commons:Athens]]` will lead you to the page titled "Athens" on [Wikimedia Commons](/Wikimedia_Commons), rendering as: commons:Athens.

Just like their more common wikilink brethren, interwiki links can also be piped. A word of caution, however: an [interlanguage link](/Help:Interlanguage_links) *must* be preceded by a colon if it is intended to be displayed inline, directly within the text, as an [inline interlanguage link](/Help:Interlanguage_links). Failure to do so will result in its relegation to the list of interlanguage links typically found at the side of the page – a fate appropriate only if it truly represents the most closely corresponding page in that other language Wikipedia. Thus, (incorporating the pipe trick, for those who value efficiency), `[[:ja:Wikilink|]]` would be the correct incantation to link to "Wikilink" on the Japanese Wikipedia. An example, for the visually inclined: ( [[:ja:URL|]] links to URL on Japanese Wikipedia).

Interwiki links, much like external links, are rendered in a subtly paler shade of blue than ordinary wikilinks. This slight chromatic distinction is a visual cue, a whisper that you are venturing beyond the immediate confines of the current project. The [MediaWiki](/MediaWiki) page formatting, in its current iteration, does not possess the foresight to detect whether these target pages actually exist. Consequently, they are **never** displayed in red. You are, in essence, taking a leap of faith.

### External links

*   Further information: [Wikipedia:External links](/Wikipedia:External_links). Because sometimes, you just need to get out.

External links are the digital equivalent of opening a door to an entirely different world. They leverage [URLs](/URL) to establish a direct connection to *any* web page, regardless of its affiliation with Wikimedia. Unlike the double-bracket embrace of internal links, external links are ensconced within **single** square brackets. Furthermore, the optional link text is separated from the URL by a space, not the enigmatic `|` pipe character that governs internal links. When rendered, these external links are typically followed by a small, rather unassuming [external link icon](/Help:External_link_icons), a subtle visual cue that you are about to depart the curated gardens of Wikipedia. For example, consider this elegant construction:

`[http://www.example.org/ link text]`

This seemingly innocuous line of code will be transformed into something far more engaging:

[link text](http://www.example.org/).

The URL itself must be specified in its glorious entirety, including the crucial protocol: for instance, `http://...` or `https://...`. Attempts to use abbreviated URLs, those concise forms that some other (non-Wikimedia) contexts might tolerate – such as `[example.org/ link text]` or `[www.example.org/ link text]` – will be met with stern disapproval. The system will simply refuse to generate a link. Instead, the raw, unadulterated link-generating markup, complete with its square brackets, will be unceremoniously copied directly into the marked-up output, leaving you with a rather unsightly "[example.org/ link text]" or "[www.example.org/ link text]". A digital scarlet letter for your lack of precision.

When, in a fit of minimalist fervor, no link text is explicitly specified, external links adopt a rather utilitarian, numbered appearance: `[http://www.example.org/some-page][http://www.example.org/some-other-page]` will become [1][2]. And should you abandon the square brackets altogether, the URL will simply display in its unadorned entirety: `http://www.example.org/` displays as http://www.example.org/.

For a more exhaustive exploration of the best practices and philosophical underpinnings of external linking, you are directed to [Help:URL § Linking to URLs](/Help:URL). Additionally, for those with a penchant for digital forensics, [Special:LinkSearch](/Special:LinkSearch) offers a powerful mechanism to unearth all pages that deign to link to a particular site.

The external link syntax, in a surprising display of versatility, can also be repurposed to link to specific pages *within* Wikipedia itself that are not readily accessible via standard wikilinks. This includes such esoteric destinations as [page history](/Help:Page_history), the raw edit view, an ancient version of a page, or the [diff](/Wikipedia:Diff) between two historical iterations. It can even be employed to craft a navigational image, for those who prefer visual cues over mere text.

Should you wish to display an external link without the distracting arrow icon – perhaps to maintain a more austere aesthetic – simply enclose the external link syntax within `<span class="plainlinks">...</span>` tags. For instance, `<span class="plainlinks">[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Help:Link&action=history this page's history]</span>`, or its more refined template equivalent `{{[Plainlink](/Template:Plainlink)}} {{plainlink|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Help:Link&action=history|name=this page's history}}`, will be rendered as: this page's history. If you find yourself frequently indulging in this particular act of digital refinement, the CharInsert gadget (which, for your convenience, can be activated under `[Preferences](/Special:Preferences) → [Gadgets](/Special:Preferences) → Editing → CharInsert`) offers an option to insert this text in its "Wiki markup" mode. A small concession to your repetitive tendencies.

#### http: and https:

In the mid-2015 epoch, Wikipedia and all its kindred Wikimedia sites underwent a significant transformation: they adopted [HTTPS](/HTTPS) as the default protocol, encrypting all traffic. This means that attempting to access a URL like `[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Link](/Help:Link)` will result in the webserver, in its infinite wisdom, redirecting you to `https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Link`. Therefore, when you find yourself crafting an external-style link to an internal page (that is, employing single square brackets, or merely a bare URL), it is **imperative** to specify `https` explicitly. This avoids the entirely needless redirect, as exemplified by `https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Help:Link&action=history`. Why waste precious milliseconds on a digital detour?

In the bygone era, when Wikipedia ambivalently tolerated access via either HTTP or HTTPS, a [protocol-relative URL](/Wikipedia:PRURL) could be employed. This allowed for the creation of an external link (or an external-style link to an internal page) that would dynamically adapt, using either `http:` or `https:` depending on how the page containing the link was originally accessed – a sophisticated maneuver like `[//www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Links]`. However, given that all Wikimedia sites now unequivocally demand HTTPS, this particular linking style has been rendered obsolete. It should no longer be used. Instead, `http:` or `https:` must be explicitly specified, with a clear preference for `https:` whenever it is available for the target site. Embrace the present, leave the past to the historians.

### Anchors

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) (Because even anchors need a quick way home.)
*   [WP:ANCHOR](/Wikipedia:ANCHOR) (The official designation for these digital mooring points.)

#### What is an "anchor"?

Links, in their most fundamental form, emanate from an origin page and point either to entire target pages – the grand destinations – or, with more surgical precision, to specific points *within* those target pages. An "anchor" is the underlying computer code, the invisible marker, that designates such a precise destination point on a target page. Links that leverage these markers are, quite logically, referred to as "anchor links."

Wikipedia, in a display of automated convenience, automatically generates anchors for all section and subsection headings. This means you don't have to manually tag every single heading. However, editors, in their quest for even greater granularity, may also create custom anchors anywhere else on a target page. This can be achieved either through direct HTML code or by employing the {{[anchor](/Template:Anchor)}} template. A crucial point to remember, often learned through bitter experience: renaming a section or subsection will, naturally, alter its automatic anchor. This leaves any pre-existing anchor links that relied on the old name adrift, without a target. To prevent such digital disconnections, editors frequently, and wisely, create a static anchor using the old heading name. It's a digital failsafe, a nod to the impermanence of even digital nomenclature.

#### Specifics

A link directed to a section title (as demonstrated in the preceding examples, if you recall them) fundamentally points to an [HTML](/HTML_element) [anchor](/HTML_element) that Wikipedia's system automatically conjures on the target page. Editors, however, are not confined to the system's automated generosity. They can meticulously craft anchors on even smaller units of text, employing the {{[Anchor](/Template:Anchor)}} template, or, for the more technically inclined, the raw [HTML](/HTML) code `<span class="anchor" id="Anchor name">...</span>`. It's like adding custom mooring points to the digital coastline.

Editors typically find themselves creating anchors for several compelling reasons:

*   To target a very specific paragraph (a level of precision rarely achieved in casual conversation; see "§ Linking to part of a section" below).
*   To facilitate the renaming of a section while simultaneously ensuring that any existing links, which rely on the *old* name, continue to function without interruption. It's a digital continuity plan.
*   To link a section using a convenient abbreviation (for more on this, consult [MOS:HEADINGS](/MOS:HEADINGS); brevity, after all, has its place).

Links to anchors possess a surprising versatility; they can also be appended to external URLs and even to interwiki links, once again utilizing the familiar `#` syntax. The digital universe, it seems, is more interconnected than one might initially perceive.

Section links, in a testament to their resilience, continue to function even when traversing page names that are, in fact, [redirects](/Help:Redirect). For instance, if [Danzig](/Danzig) serves as a redirect to [Gdańsk](/Gda%C5%84sk), then `[Danzig#History](/Danzig)` will, with admirable precision, direct the user to the "History" section within the article about Gdańsk. Furthermore, it is entirely possible, and often desirable, for the target of a redirect itself to be defined as a specific section or anchor within a page (though, be warned, these only function correctly if JavaScript is enabled – a minor technical hurdle). Indeed, [according to the Manual of Style](/MOS:SECTLINK), it is often preferable to explicitly define such redirects and then utilize them when linking to those specific sections or anchors, rather than resorting to the more verbose `[[Page name#Section or anchor name|displayed text]]` or `{{Section link| Page name | Section name }}` syntax. The rationale? Should the section or anchored text eventually blossom into its own standalone article, links that employ the redirect will seamlessly transition without requiring a laborious rewrite. It's a proactive approach to digital evolution.

Consider, for example, that [Wikipedia:Section link](/Wikipedia:Section_link) is a redirect specifically crafted to point to the `Help:Link#Anchors` section on this very page. A peculiar quirk of this mechanism, however, is that if one were to append an *additional* section name when employing such a link, it would override the section already specified by the redirect. Thus, `[Wikipedia:Section link#Interwiki links](/Wikipedia:Section_link)` would, counterintuitively, lead to the "Interwiki links" section of this page. Such overriding of section redirects should, as a general rule, be assiduously avoided. It leads to confusion, and confusion, as we know, leads to suffering.

The {{[Visible anchor](/Template:Visible_anchor)}} template offers another layer of functionality: it can be employed to create an anchor that is not only functional but also visually highlighted when it is linked to (click here for an example, if you dare). The template's first parameter will serve a dual purpose, acting as both the anchor itself and the displayed text (though the `|text=` parameter can be invoked to provide an alternative display text, should your aesthetic sensibilities demand it).

#### Duplicate section names

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) (A quick way to acknowledge this digital redundancy.)
*   [WP:DUPSECTNAME](/Wikipedia:DUPSECTNAME) (The official designation for this particular headache.)

In the sprawling landscape of a target page, it is not uncommon for multiple sections to bear the exact same title. When this digital redundancy occurs, a link directed solely to that title will, with unwavering predictability, point only to the *first* section adorned with that particular appellation. Should your intent be to link to a subsequent section bearing the identical title, or even a title that differs only in its capitalization (e.g., "Example" versus "EXAMPLE"), you must append `_2`, `_3`, and so forth, directly to the linked title, **without a space** (or, for the truly unconventional, `2`, `3`, and so on *with* a space). This numerical suffix serves as a disambiguator, counting sequentially from the very top of the target page, and, crucially, without any regard for whether a section is a primary section or a mere subsection. For instance, if a page is plagued by multiple sections all titled "History," they can be precisely targeted as "History," "History_2" (or "History 2"), and so on. It's a system born of necessity, for when human creativity in naming conventions fails.

#### Linking to part of a section

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) (For those who prefer to cut to the chase, or the specific sentence.)
*   [WP:LINKPART](/WP:LINKPART) (The official decree for granular linking.)
*   See also: § Table row linking. Because even tables deserve their moment in the spotlight.

Anchors, those versatile digital mooring points, can extend their reach even further, allowing you to link to *any* specific part of a section, no matter how minute. Imagine, if you will, the desire to link directly to the fifth sentence of a particularly verbose section. The solution is elegant in its simplicity: you strategically place an anchor at the very genesis of that sentence. From that point forward, you can then link to this newly minted anchor with the same effortless grace as you would any other anchor. It's digital surgery, performed with textual precision.

However, a caveat, as always, lurks in the shadows. Just as with section names, the specter of duplicate anchor names arises. Should you inadvertently create multiple anchors with the same name, a link targeting that name will, with frustrating predictability, only ever connect to the *first* instance. Since anchors themselves are not visibly displayed – they are the silent workhorses of navigation – you are afforded a significantly greater degree of freedom in concocting truly unique anchor names. A prudent strategy might involve appending the current date and time to the anchor name (for example, christening an anchor for a section "ThisSection" with something like `{{Anchor|ThisSection2014-09-22-18-05a1}}`). It's a digital timestamp, ensuring uniqueness across the vast expanse of time and edits.

Anchors, in their boundless adaptability, can be deployed almost anywhere. This includes, but is not limited to, the very beginning of a clause, or even nestled within notes and citations. However, a word of caution for the intrepid: it is highly advisable to conduct preliminary tests within your [sandbox](/Draft:Sandbox) before attempting to unleash some exotic, never-before-seen anchor location upon the unsuspecting mainspace. Furthermore, the anchor *must* be positioned after any indicators that are exclusively recognized at the start of a line (such as `==` or `===` for new sections, `*` for new bullet points, `:` for indentation). While the anchor itself should still function correctly in such scenarios, the start-of-line indicator typically will not. And, perhaps more alarmingly, you might not always immediately notice this subtle breakage, especially if you are, as is often the case, operating under the tyrannical yoke of a deadline.

A small, select cadre of special anchor names exists. For a detailed exposition on these, consult "§ Table row linking." Because even the most mundane elements of digital structure possess their own quirks.

#### Table row linking

To meticulously craft an anchor for a specific row within a table – a testament to granular control – consult [Help:Tables and locations § Section link or map link to a row anchor](/Help:Tables_and_locations). However, be forewarned: `[[#top]]` and `[[#toc]]` are sacrosanct, reserved names. The former, `[[#top]]`, unfailingly links to the very apex of a page, while the latter, `[[#toc]]`, directs you to the hallowed [table of contents](/Table_of_contents). These are not for your casual repurposing.

### Piped link

*   See also: [Help:Pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick). Because sometimes, the truth is best presented with a flourish.
*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) (A quick way to the pipe, for the truly impatient.)
*   [H:PIPE](/H:PIPE) (The official designation for this digital conduit.)

A piped link is a sophisticated form of either an internal link or an [interwiki link](/Help:Interwiki_linking) where both the ultimate destination (the link target) and the visible label (the link label) are explicitly specified. This precision is absolutely essential in situations where the target and the label are not identical, and, crucially, where the link label cannot be derived by simply extending the last word of the link target. It's a nuanced distinction, often missed by the uninitiated:

*   `[[cheese]]` (Here, the label is identical to the target, so no pipe is needed)
    This produces [cheese](/Cheese), which, predictably, links to the article titled "Cheese." A straightforward affair.

*   `[[cheese]]s` (In this instance, the label is the target augmented by an extension, in this case, "s"; still, no pipe is needed due to agglutination)
    This produces [cheeses](/Cheese), leading to the article "Cheese." The system, in its wisdom, understands the pluralization.

*   `[[blue cheese|cheese]]` (Here, the label is merely a component of the target, thus demanding the pipe)
    This produces [cheese](/Blue_cheese), linking to the article "Blue cheese." A subtle redirection.

*   `[[cheese|blue cheese]]` (Conversely, the label is the target plus additional text, "blue," again necessitating the pipe)
    This produces [blue cheese](/Cheese), linking to the article "Cheese." The label now provides more context than the target.

*   `[[cheese|that stuff]]` (The label, in this bold maneuver, is entirely distinct from the target, making the pipe an absolute requirement)
    This produces [that stuff](/Cheese), linking to the article "Cheese." A complete digital disguise.

This ingenious mechanism permits the linking of a specific word or phrase directly within the flow of an article's text, rather than relegating it to a less elegant "see also" section. This holds true even if the chosen wording does not precisely align with the canonical name of the target page. With a suitably configured browser and depending on one's meticulously set [preferences](/Help:Preferences), the discerning user can still divine the true link target: simply hovering the cursor over the link (a "mouseover" event) will cause the target's name to materialize in a hover [tooltip](/Tooltip), and often, it will also be displayed in the browser's status bar. It's a small concession to transparency.

For illustrative purposes:

`[[Train station|station]]`

will manifest as: [station](/Train_station)

This particular technique proves immensely valuable when the generic term "station" is employed within an article primarily concerned with trains. From the immediate context, it becomes unequivocally clear that a train station is the intended destination. Such a piped link offers a more seamless and user-friendly experience than, say, a direct link to [station](/Station), which might, to the user's frustration, lead to a disambiguation page – a digital crossroads that demands further cognitive effort.

The term "piped" itself refers, quite literally, to the use of the `|` pipe character. This character, a digital separator, serves to demarcate the "good description" (the link label) from the "actual link" (the target). Its nomenclature is, in fact, derived from another, unrelated application; for a deeper dive into its origins, consult [Pipe (computing)](/Pipe_(computing)).

For those who crave efficiency, several clever "tricks" exist to achieve the same result with fewer keystrokes:

*   Leaving the section to the right of the pipe empty – this is the famed "[pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick)."
*   Conversely, leaving the section to the left empty – this is the less common, but equally intriguing, "inverse pipe trick."
*   Simply attaching text directly to the link, as demonstrated by `[[train]]s`, a technique elaborated upon in [MOS:PIPE](/MOS:PIPE).

#### Using a redirect as alternative

An alternative strategy to employing a piped link involves the judicious use of a [redirect page](/Help:Redirect). For instance, it is entirely superfluous to write `[[Mark Twain|Samuel Clemens]]`. The page [Samuel Clemens](/Samuel_Clemens) is, in fact, a redirect that points directly to [Mark Twain](/Mark_Twain). Therefore, simply writing `[[Samuel Clemens]]` is perfectly sufficient. It's a more elegant solution, leveraging existing digital infrastructure. A minor drawback, however, is that the "[Related changes](/Help:Related_changes)" feature will only display the changes made to the redirect page itself, not to the ultimate target of the redirect. A small price to pay for elegance.

#### Automatic conversion of wikitext with the pipe trick

*   See also: [Help:Pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick). Because the system, sometimes, tries to be helpful.

If, in a moment of either genius or forgetfulness, you leave the portion of a piped link after the `|` character empty, the system, in its infinite wisdom, will automatically [convert](/Help:Automatic_conversion_of_wikitext) it into an abbreviated form of the linked page. This conversion follows a specific, predictable set of rules:

*   Any word found before the first colon (`:`) – including the colon itself – is summarily removed. This initial word may, or may not, constitute a legitimate namespace prefix (such as "Help:") or an interwiki prefix (such as "commons:"). If the page name is itself preceded by a colon, the term "first" refers to the first colon *after* this initial one.
*   If the page name concludes with text enclosed in parentheses, that entire parenthetical segment will be unceremoniously removed.
*   Should there be no parentheses, but a comma exists, the comma and every character following it are excised.
*   The resulting link will retain whatever case was originally used in the pipe-tricked portion.

Much like the behavior of the three or four tildes used for signing on Talk pages, and the employment of `subst`, the result of this pipe trick conversion will visibly appear in the preview itself. However, the underlying conversion within the edit box will not yet be displayed. To witness the transformation in the raw wikitext, you must press "Show changes." It's a subtle distinction, often missed.

Category tag
The sort key syntax of a category, while structurally similar to a piped link, also allows for the pipe trick. However, it is, in most practical applications, utterly useless in this context. A testament to the system's occasional over-engineering.

Examples using colons
*   `[[Help:Template|]]` is converted to `[[Help:Template|Template]]`, which is then rendered as [Template](/Help:Template). A clean, concise presentation.
*   `[[Music: My life|]]` is converted to `[[Music: My life| My life]]`, which renders as My life. Despite "Music:" not being a recognized namespace (thus, the space after the colon is not automatically removed), the shortcut, surprisingly, still functions.
*   `[[w:en:Pipe (computing)|]]` is converted to `[[w:en:Pipe (computing)|en:Pipe]]`, which renders as [en:Pipe](/Pipe_(computing)). A slightly more verbose, but equally functional, outcome.

Case examples
*   `[[pipe (computing)|]]` is converted to `[[pipe (computing)|pipe]]`, which is rendered as [pipe](/Pipe_(computing)). The system respects the lowercase.
*   `[[Pipe (computing)|]]` is converted to `[[Pipe (computing)|Pipe]]`, which is rendered as [Pipe](/Pipe_(computing)). The system respects the uppercase.

Comma example
*   `[[commons:Boston, Massachusetts|]]` is converted to `[[commons:Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]]`, which is rendered as Boston. A neat truncation.

Other examples
*   [Parameters](/Help:Templates) and [variables](/Help:Magic_words):
    *   `[[w:{{{1}}}|]]` does **not** automatically expand to `[[w:{{{1}}}|{{{1}}}]]`. The system, in this case, refuses to guess.
    *   Calling the template with a specific value for parameter 1 will only yield a working link if substitution (`subst:`) is employed. A subtle, yet crucial, distinction.
*   `[[w:en:{{FULLPAGENAME}}|]]` does **not** automatically expand to `[[w:en:{{FULLPAGENAME}}|en:{{FULLPAGENAME}}]]`. The system, again, exhibits caution.
*   `[[m:{{FULLPAGENAME}}|]]` does **not** automatically expand to `[[m:{{FULLPAGENAME}}|{{FULLPAGENAME}}]]`. It seems the system prefers explicit instructions for these dynamic elements.

The following examples, when processed, appear as:

*   [a](/Project:a)
*   [project:a](/W:project:a)
*   [project:a](/De:project:a)
*   [project:a](/Wiktionary:project:a)
*   [de:project:a](/Wiktionary:de:project:a)
*   [project:a](/Wikibooks:project:a)
*   [project:a](/Wikiquote:project:a)
*   [project:a](/Wikisource:project:a)
*   [[w:en:Help:Link|]] (Note: This is the raw wikitext, as the full expansion of `{{FULLPAGENAME}}` only occurs on save or preview under certain conditions, as mentioned above.)
*   en:Help:Link (This is the *result* if `{{FULLPAGENAME}}` were "Help:Link" and the pipe trick applied.)
*   [[m:Help:Link|]] (Again, raw wikitext.)
*   Help:Link (The *result* if `{{FULLPAGENAME}}` were "Help:Link" and the pipe trick applied.)

#### Inverse pipe trick

The inverse pipe trick, a lesser-known but equally potent maneuver, demonstrates a fascinating contextual awareness. When you are on a page titled "A (c)," simply typing `[[|B]]` is automatically converted by the system into `[[B (c)|B]]`. The system, in essence, guesses your intent by inferring the parenthetical disambiguator from the current page's title.

Similarly, if you find yourself on a page designated "A, c," the same `[[|B]]` incantation will be automatically transformed into `[[B, c|B]]`. The comma-separated context is also intelligently absorbed. It's almost as if the system is trying to anticipate your every move, a minor act of digital mind-reading.

[Further examples are here](/Help:Pipe_trick), for those who wish to delve deeper into the nuances of this clever shortcut.

### Subpage links

A wikilink, in its purest form, demands a `[[ fullpagename ]]`. This explicit declaration of the full page name is rarely optional, save for one specific scenario: when the link is either directed to or originating from a [subpage](/Help:Subpage).

A wikilink pointing to its immediate parent page can be elegantly expressed as `[[../]]`. And remarkably, even though no explicit page name is provided within the brackets, the [fullpagename](/Wikipedia:Pgn) of the parent is dutifully rendered. Conversely, on a parent page, a wikilink to one of its subpages can employ the concise `[[/ subpagename ]]` syntax, which then renders merely the subpagename. It's a system designed for familial digital relationships.

A crucial, and often frustrating, caveat: although subpages *can* be created within the main article space, the full functionality of subpage linking does not entirely extend to that realm. It's a feature with limitations.

However, in other namespaces, subpage linking works with admirable predictability, allowing you to link to any page nestled beneath a designated root parent page:

*   Section linking within a subpage hierarchy: `[[../# section ]]`.
*   Linking between child subpages: `[[../ [subpagename](/Wikipedia:Pgn) ]]`.
*   Ascending to the parent's parent: `[[../../]]`.
*   Even incorporating the versatile `[[../|` [pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick).
*   And, for the truly advanced, including [transclusions](/Help:Transclusion): `{{../}}` and `{{/ subpagename }}`.

Consider, for a moment, the sheer scale: there are approximately 140 subpages stemming from the [Manual of Style](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Contents), organized into 97 distinct branches. Of these, 35 branches boast two subpages, and a select 5 branches are blessed with three subpages. In such a sprawling hierarchy, subpage links become invaluable, saving countless keystrokes and preventing an epidemic of carpal tunnel syndrome. Imagine editing this closely related group of fullpagenames:

[Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Signatures](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Signatures)
[Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Data tables tutorial](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Data_tables_tutorial)
[Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Data tables tutorial/Internal guidelines](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Data_tables_tutorial/Internal_guidelines)

The following table illustrates the elegant brevity achievable with subpage linking:

| On subpagename          | You type                                | You get                                                      | Links to                                                      |
| :---------------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Data tables tutorial    | `[[../]]`                               | [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility) | Parent                                                        |
| Internal​guidelines     | `[[../../]]`                            | [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility) | Grandparent                                                   |
| Accessibility           | `[[/Signatures]]`                       | [/Signatures](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Signatures) | Child                                                         |
| Accessibility           | `[[/Signatures / ]]`                    | Signatures                                                   | Child                                                         |
| Data tables tutorial    | `[[../Signatures]]`                     | [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Signatures](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Signatures) | Sibling                                                       |
| Data tables tutorial    | `[[../Signatures/]]`                    | Signatures                                                   | Sibling                                                       |
| Internal​guidelines     | `[[../../Signatures]]`                  | [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Signatures](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Signatures) | Uncle                                                         |
| Signatures              | `[[../Data tables tutorial/Internal guidelines]]` | [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Data tables tutorial/Internal guidelines](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Accessibility/Data_tables_tutorial/Internal_guidelines) | Nephew                                                        |

To truly grasp the intricate array of subpage variables and markup, extending four levels deep, visit [/one/two/three/four](/Help:Link/one/two/three/four). From that digital vantage point, you can then ascend to level two at one/two.

The markup `[[../]]` is generally understood to address the `basepagename`. However, a perplexing quirk arises when a pagename itself incorporates a `/` slash character (which is, regrettably, permitted). In such cases, the `basepagename/subpagename` variables' characters become skewed, leading to unexpected results. To fully comprehend this digital anomaly, and to witness how the addition of an extra `../` construct can rectify the resulting [redlink](/Wikipedia:Redlink), navigate to [/sub/page/name1/sub/page/name2/subpage level 3](/Help:Link/sub/page/name1/sub/page/name2/subpage_level_3). From there, you can further explore by venturing to sub/page/name2. It's a journey into the heart of digital weirdness.

A small but helpful observation: the very top of every subpage proudly displays the [navigation links](/Breadcrumb_(navigation)) to all its parent subpagenames. These serve as invaluable breadcrumbs, allowing you to effortlessly gauge the current level within the hierarchy and to decipher the appropriate linking constructs.

For those who demand further enlightenment:

*   Consult [Wikipedia:Page name#Subpagename and basepagename](/Wikipedia:Page_name).
*   To initiate a subpage, simply employ a [red link](/Help:Red_link). It's an act of digital creation.
*   Explore `m:Help:Link#Subpage feature` for cross-wiki insights.
*   Peruse the examples at `m:Link/a/b` and `m:Help:Link/a/b`.

### Special pages links

*   Main page: [Help:Special page § Linking to or listing special pages](/Help:Special_page). Because some pages are more special than others.

To forge a link to one of these uniquely designated special pages, the syntax is straightforward:

`[[Special:PrefixIndex/HMS]]` → [Special:PrefixIndex/HMS](/Special:PrefixIndex/HMS)

However, a significant constraint exists: because the ampersand character (`&`) is, for reasons lost to the mists of time, disallowed within ordinary link targets, it is impossible to construct a standard wikilink containing `&action=edit` or `&redirect=no` directly within the URL query string. These particular parameters, while crucial for certain functionalities, are simply incompatible with the standard wikilink syntax. In such scenarios, one must resort to templates or magic words. Consult "§ Links containing URL query strings" for the prescribed workarounds.

For example, you can employ a template such as {{[Plain link](/Template:Plain_link)}} to meticulously encode a Wikimedia URL link, particularly one that points to a special page adorned with various parameters.

`{{Plain link|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Log&logid=79269392|name=15:21, 8 December 2016}}`

This rather verbose incantation yields a clean, unadorned link:

15:21, 8 December 2016

### Changing link appearance

The ways in which various links manifest themselves visually within browsers, as meticulously detailed above, represent the default display styles inherent in the default [skin](/Wikipedia:Skin). However, users, in their perpetual quest for customization, possess the agency to alter their perception of these links:

*   By simply opting for a different skin, they can transform the entire visual aesthetic.
*   By applying a custom [user style](/Help:User_style) utilizing CSS (for the precise incantations, consult [Help:Link color](/Help:Link_color)), they can meticulously control every chromatic detail.
*   By adjusting the "Underline links" value nestled within the [Appearance tab](/Special:Preferences) of their [user preferences](/Help:Preferences), they can dictate the very presence of digital underlines.

### Hatnote links

A hatnote, as its name rather quaintly suggests, is a brief note that perches atop a paragraph, much like a hat atop a head. Such as the one below, a subtle signpost in the digital wilderness.

*   Main page: [Wikipedia:Hatnote](/Wikipedia:Hatnote). Because even hats need their own main page.

Occasionally, an article might contain a section that delves into a concept which, in its own right, commands a dedicated, standalone article. In such instances, the elegant solution is to add a 'Main page' link, precisely as demonstrated here. This can be accomplished by invoking the {{[Main](/Template:Main)}} template. For those navigating the [visual editor](/Wikipedia:VisualEditor), this template can be conjured via `Insert > Template > Main`, subsequently setting the 'Page 1' parameter to the page intended for reference. The 'Label 1' parameter offers an optional means to customize the text displayed for the link, should your aesthetic sensibilities demand it. A generous allowance of up to five such links may be specified. Within the more austere confines of the source editor, the code `{{Main| page1 | page2 |l1 = label1 |l2 = label2 }}` can be employed, where `page1` and `label1` correspond directly to their counterparts in the visual editor. Here too, up to five of these digital signposts are permitted. The following hatnote templates, along with their customary texts, also grace the digital landscape:

*   {{[Main list](/Template:Main_list)}}: For a more comprehensive list, see Article. A polite nudge towards greater detail.
*   {{[Broader](/Template:Broader)}}: For broader coverage on this topic, see Article. An invitation to expand one's intellectual horizons.
*   {{[Further](/Template:Further)}}: Further information: Article. A direct pointer to more extensive knowledge.
*   {{[See also](/Template:See_also)}}: See also: Article. A classic, timeless suggestion for related content.

### Hover tooltips

In the majority of contemporary browsers, the act of holding the cursor motionless over a link (a phenomenon colloquially known as a [mouseover](/Mouseover)) conjures a hover [tooltip](/Tooltip). This small, ephemeral box contains the text derived from the link's [HTML](/HTML) title attribute. MediaWiki – the very software that underpins Wikipedia's vast digital edifice – thoughtfully sets this attribute. If the link in question is a wikilink, the tooltip will reveal the target page name (devoid of any section indication, for brevity). If it's an interwiki link, the page name will be presented with its appropriate prefix. And for the untamed [external link](/Help:External_links), the tooltip will display the full link address ([URL](/URL)). (This particular feature, for those who find it intrusive, can be disabled within the [user preferences](/Help:Preferences).) The browser itself may also, in its own discretion, display similar information, including any section indication, within the status bar. It's a subtle dance of information delivery.

For these specific effects, a piped link proves useful even if it is not ultimately followed. Consider, for example, its utility in displaying the meaning of an acronym without forcing the user to navigate away. For those who desire a hover tooltip without the cumbersome necessity of an actual link, the {{[Tooltip](/Template:Tooltip)}} template offers a precise solution. It's digital magic, without the commitment.

### Disallowed characters

A link whose target dares to contain characters deemed "disallowed" (for a definitive list of these digital pariahs, consult [WP:Page name](/Wikipedia:Page_name)) will be displayed without any of the customary markup. It simply sits there, inert, as though it never even tried to be a link, as in `[[A{b}]]`. A stark reminder that rules, even in the digital realm, have consequences.

Automatic conversions are meticulously performed for [non-literal characters](/Help:Special_characters) found within wiki and interwiki links. For instance, `[[Help:Page%20name]]` is gracefully transformed into [Help:Page name](/Help:Page_name). However, the inverse holds true for external links; here, literal characters are, with a curious inversion, converted into their non-literal counterparts. An example: most browsers will dutifully convert `.../wiki/!` to `.../wiki/%21`. It's a digital paradox, for those who appreciate such things.

Certain characters within a web address link *must* be represented as [escape characters](/Escape_character). This is not a suggestion, but a mandate, because these characters are reserved for Wikipedia's own internal editing mechanisms. Examples of these digital escapees include `%5B` for `[`, `%5D` for `]`, `%3C` for `<`, `%3E` for `>`, `%7B` for `{`, `%7D` for `}`, `%7C` for `|`, and `%26` for `&`. For a more exhaustive catalog of these elusive characters, delve into the arcane world of [percent encoding](/Percent_encoding). A critical warning: [Numeric character references](/Numeric_character_reference) (e.g., `&#91;` or `&#x5B;`) should **never** be employed in external links. The reason? The ubiquitous ampersand character (`&`) holds a special, reserved meaning within a URL, and its misuse can lead to digital chaos.

In instances of excessive character escaping, where the manual process becomes tedious and error-prone, an automatic percent encoder – such as the one conveniently provided at W3 Schools (specifically, the second JavaScript form under "URL Encoding Functions") – is likely the simplest and most sane solution. For example, meticulously pasting `Help talk:Citation Style 1/Archive 41#{{Cite book}} and |contribution problems` into that form yields the rather imposing wikilink `[[Help%20talk%3ACitation%20Style%201%2FArchive%2041%23%7B%7BCite%20book%7D%7D%20and%20%7Ccontribution%20problems]]`. This, miraculously, appears as [Help talk:Citation Style 1/Archive 41#{{Cite book}} and |contribution problems](/Help_talk:Citation_Style_1/Archive_41), precisely as desired. [2] A small price to pay for sanity.

### Links containing ampersands

Because the [ampersand character](/Ampersand) (`&`) is, as previously noted, strictly disallowed within ordinary link targets, it presents a peculiar challenge. Consequently, it is impossible to create a standard wikilink that directly incorporates `&action=edit` or `&redirect=no` into its URL query string. These specific parameters, while seemingly minor, are often invaluable, particularly within user pages. Furthermore, a redirect page, in its quiet existence, can possess categories, and one might, in a moment of digital efficiency, wish to view or edit these with a single click. Fortunately, for these specific scenarios, three distinct methods exist to forge these otherwise impossible links:

*   You can employ the {{[Querylink](/Template:Querylink)}} template. This ingenious construct allows you to append arbitrary query parameters to a Wikipedia page URL. For instance, `{{Querylink|Help:Link|qs=action=history|this page's history}}` will produce the functional link [this page's history](/Help:Link).
*   Alternatively, the {{[Plain link](/Template:Plain_link)}} template can be utilized to meticulously encode a Wikimedia URL link. Consider this example: `{{Plain link|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Log&logid=79269392|name=query}}` yields the link query. It's a robust solution for complex URLs.
*   Finally, one can harness the power of the [magic word](/Help:Magic_words) `fullurl`. To append `action=edit` to a URL query string, for example, you could construct `[{{fullurl:Help:Link|action=history}} this page's history]`, which will render as this page's history. A crucial distinction to note: this method will render the link as an *external* link rather than an internal one. For this reason, such links might not appear in the "What links here" queries associated with the target page. A subtle compromise, but often a necessary one.

### Link reports

*   Further information: [Help:What links here](/Help:What_links_here). Because sometimes, you need to know who's talking about you.

The navigable links that point to a given page fall into several categories: these include standard wikilinks, redirects, and those peculiar external-styled wikilinks.
The {{[orphan](/Template:Orphan)}} tag, a digital cry for help, can be placed on pages that languish without any incoming wikilinks. A sad fate, indeed.

#### To a page

Each individual link pointing to a page is, fundamentally, a link to a *name*. [3] It is a lamentable truth that no single report, in its current incarnation, is capable of revealing *all* links to the content itself. A fragmented digital reality.

The [What links here](/Help:What_links_here) tool, a ubiquitous feature present on every page, will diligently report all wikilinks and all redirects that point to the content of that specific page. (As a bonus, you even get the wikilinks that point to those redirects. It's a layered system.) The [search](/H:S) parameter `linksto`, however, is more selective, finding only direct wikilinks. Both of these tools are capable of reporting (invisible) wikilinks that are generated via a transclusion through a {{[template](/Help:Template)}}. The fundamental difference between them is subtle but significant: `linksto` provides a quantifiable count of links to a *page name*, whereas "What Links Here" offers a more comprehensive map of links to the page as *content*. [4]

#### To a section

The navigable links that specifically target a section within a page encompass wikilinks, redirects, and URL-styled wikilinks.
The distinction between a redirect and a wikilink becomes most pronounced when a redirect is designed to target a specific section. In such cases, you are, paradoxically, unable to append your own `# section` to it, even though it may visually appear as `[[ page name ]]`. A wikilink that explicitly targets a section, and is visibly represented as `[[ page name # section name ]]`, possesses the flexibility to link to that section either through its canonical page name (the actual title displayed on the page containing the content) or through the page name of any redirect that points to it. In the latter scenario, the "page name" refers, of course, to the name of the redirect page itself.

To meticulously uncover all wikilinks that point to a particular section, a single report is insufficient. It demands the execution of two or more distinct reports.

*   "Show redirects only," an external tool accessible from the "What links here" page, is designed to report redirects that specifically target the content of a section. (Regardless of the page name you feed it, it will dutifully return all relevant redirect page names.) You must, however, exercise discernment: look beyond any "No anchor or section" group of redirects, and ignore any "invalid" sections. Your goal is to ascertain if your particular section name is explicitly listed. If it is, then the redirect pages listed beneath it are likely to have incoming links that will, in turn, correctly navigate to that section. [5] (While "What Links Here" also offers a "show redirects" report, it lacks the crucial detail of specifying *if* the redirect actually points to any particular section.)
*   Once you've identified any relevant redirect pages in the preceding step, you must then employ "What Links Here" on *each* of those redirect pages. It's a multi-stage investigation.
*   Finally, the {{Links to}} template can be utilized to generate a collection of search links, each of which will, in turn, report some of the links pointing to a section. This template, however, operates on only one page name at a time. For each search link it generates, you must manually alter the page name within the query to correspond to each identified redirect, in sequence.

The more redirects that are involved, the more reports you are condemned to run. Such is the price of digital thoroughness. If, by some miracle, no redirects are involved, a single report from "Links to" will suffice. A rare moment of simplicity.

#### From a page

To generate a report detailing all links originating *from* a specific page, the process is refreshingly straightforward: you simply enumerate all the wikilinks present on that page.

*   [Wikipedia:Tools/Editing tools § Relink](/Wikipedia:Tools/Editing_tools) offers a utility capable of counting wikilinks from a copy of the wikitext residing on your local machine.
*   Certain [text editors support](/Wikipedia:Text_editor_support) the highlighting and counting of occurrences of the `[[...]]` pattern.
*   The Wikipedia [web API](/Application_programming_interface) is a powerful interface that accepts queries via URL. [6]

One method of dispatching a query to the API involves constructing an external link (as detailed in "§ External links"). For example, by crafting an external link very much akin to a search link, you can send the API a request to enumerate the link properties of "[wp:example](/Wikipedia:Example)." The API, in its intelligent parsing, should correctly interpret this as "Wikipedia:Example," corresponding to page ID 25263910.

| What you type                                                                | What you get when fullpagename is [wp:example](/Wikipedia:Example) |
| :--------------------------------------------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `[//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=query&prop=links&pllimit=500&titles= fullpagename your label ]` | [your label](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=query&prop=links&pllimit=500&titles=Wikipedia:Example) |

*   The report, consistent with the norms of RESTful APIs, is delivered in [JSON](/JSON) format.
*   The `pageid` can be conveniently retrieved from the "Page information" link present on every page.
*   Observe that the `titles` parameter is plural. (It is designed to accept multiple fullpagenames or page IDs, delimited by the `|` pipe character.)
*   The number of links returned by this particular query is, by design, capped at 500, as dictated by the URL you constructed. For guidance on how to safely retrieve a larger number of links, consult `mw:API:Query`. For instance, [Operating system](/Operating_system) boasts 510 wikilinks, a number that would exceed this default limit.

To make a page register as having an incoming link, but without actually displaying the link itself, you can create a link to it, but cleverly label it with a single space character using the pipe trick: `[[ pagename | ]]`. It's a ghostly connection, visible only to the system.

### Additional link-related functions

For a detailed exposition on the curious effect that links exert on date formatting, consult [Help:Date formatting and linking](/Help:Date_formatting_and_linking). It's more complex than you'd think.

Another feature inextricably linked to the presence of links is [related changes](/Help:Related_changes). This utility makes it possible to view recent modifications made to *all* pages that are linked from the current page (or, if the page in question is a category page, all pages that are members of that category). It's a window into the interconnected web of digital revisions.

For information pertaining to the intricate process of linking to pages directly from an image, consult `mw:Extension:ImageMap`. Because images, too, deserve to be interactive.

Several [templates](/Help:Template) have been meticulously crafted to streamline the process of linking (though, it must be noted, they are not typically employed within the main article space). These include the concise {{[tl](/Template:Tl)}} and the slightly more verbose {{[tlx](/Template:Tlx)}} for linking to templates, as well as {{[cl](/Template:Cl)}} and {{[lc](/Template:Lc)}} for linking to categories. A more comprehensive collection can be found lurking within [Category:Internal link templates](/Category:Internal_link_templates).

### Conversion to canonical form

*   Further information: `mw:Manual:Title.php § Canonical forms`. Because the system always knows the *true* name.

As previously described, with a level of detail that borders on the excessive, if a link target commences with a lowercase letter, the system, in its infinite wisdom, will interpret it as though it began with the equivalent capital letter. Should the target encompass a [namespace](/Help:Namespace) prefix, then the entirety of that prefix, along with the very first character immediately following the colon, is treated as case-insensitive. Thus, `[uSeR:jimbo Wales](/User:Jimbo_Wales)` will, with admirable consistency, link to [User:Jimbo Wales](/User:Jimbo_Wales).

Within the sacred confines of link targets, spaces and underscores (which, for all practical purposes, are considered equivalent) are summarily ignored if they appear at the very beginning, at the very end, or immediately preceding or following the colon that demarcates a namespace prefix. Furthermore, any consecutive spaces or underscores are ruthlessly collapsed and treated as a single space. Hence, `[_User_: Jimbo_ __ Wales__](/User:Jimbo_Wales)` will, despite its visual cacophony, link to [User:Jimbo Wales](/User:Jimbo_Wales). It's a system that values internal consistency over superficial presentation.

[HTML character references](/HTML_character_reference) and [percent-encoded](/Percent_encoding) characters are, without exception, replaced by their raw character equivalents. For example, `[[d&eacute;partement]]` produces [département](/D%C3%A9partement), and `[[%40]]` produces [@](/@). Links that, upon resolution, point to [invalid page titles](/Wikipedia:Naming_conventions_(technical_restrictions)) are simply displayed as unmarked-up wikitext. The system, in such cases, refuses to dignify them with any special formatting.

Titles indicated by wikilinks are invariably displayed in their canonical form (meaning, with corrected capitalization and any superfluous spaces or underscores meticulously removed, as previously detailed) in the following digital locations:

*   Within [transclusion](/Help:Transclusion) tags that point to non-existent pages: `{{qwsazx}}` yields Template:Qwsazx. The system cannot create what isn't there, but it can acknowledge the attempt.
*   In hover tooltips and in the status bar (if your browser deigns to display such things) when the mouse cursor glides over the link.
*   On [redirect](/Help:Redirect) pages.
*   Within the [category](/Wikipedia:Category) box.

The prefixes found in [interwiki links](/Help:Interwiki_linking) are treated with a similar logic to namespace prefixes: they are insensitive to case and to the presence of spaces before and after the colon. However, a crucial distinction exists: the first character immediately following the colon is **not** automatically capitalized (whether it is interpreted as a capital or not depends entirely on the specific configuration of the target wiki. A small, but significant, variable in the digital equation).

